		<item>
		<title>What the Google Antitrust Ruling Means for Advertisers &#038; Small Businesses</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-antitrust-ruling</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Rob Glover]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 12 Aug 2024 16:00:02 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Marketing News & Insights]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=85027</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>A recent federal court ruling could upend how Google operates. What will it mean for small businesses?</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-antitrust-ruling">What the Google Antitrust Ruling Means for Advertisers &#038; Small Businesses</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Last week, <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-08-05/google-loses-doj-antitrust-suit-over-search" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the judge in the Google antitrust trial ruled</a> that the company has illegally monopolized web search. Legal and tech experts are calling it a <a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2024/08/05/google-antitrust-lawsuit-00172678">historic win</a> for the Department of Justice and a sign of even bigger upheavals to come for <a href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2024/08/05/google-loses-antitrust-case/74680072007/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">search</a> and <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/06/technology/google-microsoft-antitrust-cases.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">big tech</a>.</p>
<p>But what does the ruling portend for those of us at ground level‚Äîthe marketers and small business owners who rely on Google to connect us with the customers who support our businesses?</p>
<p>Today, we‚Äôll explain how we got to this point, what comes next, and share what a few experts believe will be the most likely effects this case will have on small businesses and search advertisers.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#a-brief-background-of-the-google-antitrust-case">A brief background of the Google antitrust case</a></li>
<li><a href="#the-ruling-and-its-potential-impacts">The ruling and its potential impacts</a></li>
<li><a href="#what-does-this-mean-for-small-businesses">What does this mean for small businesses?</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="a-brief-background-of-the-google-antitrust-case"></div>
<h2>A brief background of the Google antitrust case</h2>
<p>In 2020, the US Justice Department, along with several US states, filed an antitrust case against Google, alleging that it illegally monopolized online search and advertising.</p>
<p>At the heart of the suit are <a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/10/27/23934961/google-antitrust-trial-defaults-search-deal-26-3-billion" target="_blank" rel="noopener">agreements Google entered</a> with companies like Apple and Samsung to make its search engine the default on various mobile devices and internet browsers. Those agreements, <a href="https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-monopolist-google-violating-antitrust-laws" target="_blank" rel="noopener">said the DOJ in its complaint</a>, helped Google become ‚Äúa monopoly gatekeeper for the internet, and one of the wealthiest companies on the planet.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/google-antitrust-case-icon.webp" alt="Google antitrust ruling - Google icon on an iphone." width="788" height="590" class="aligncenter wp-image-85039 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/google-antitrust-case-icon.webp 788w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/google-antitrust-case-icon-480x359.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 788px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The 10-week trial kicked off in September of 2023 and included testimonies from Google, Microsoft, and Apple, among many others. US District Judge Amit Mehta delivered his ruling on August 5.</p>
<div id="the-ruling-and-its-potential-impacts"></div>
<h2>The ruling and its potential impacts</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-judge-describes-how-google-built-defended-illegal-search-monopoly-2024-08-05/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Judge Mehta ruled</a> that Google‚Äôs default agreements created a monopoly on online search and advertising‚Äîwhich have, in turn, blocked competition and throttled innovation. ‚ÄúThe distribution agreements have caused a third key anticompetitive effect: They have reduced the incentive to invest and innovate in search,‚Äù he said in his ruling.</p>
<p>In 2022, for example, Google paid Apple <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-01/google-s-payments-to-apple-reached-20-billion-in-2022-cue-says?embedded-checkout=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener">$20 billion</a> to maintain its spot as the default search engine for iOS devices. ‚ÄúSure, users can access Google&#8217;s rivals by switching the default search access point or by downloading a rival search app or browser. But the market reality is that users rarely do so,‚Äù <a href="https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-judge-describes-how-google-built-defended-illegal-search-monopoly-2024-08-05/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Judge Mehta</a> concluded.</p>
<p>The ruling in this trial is step one. Next up is a September 6 hearing to decide what changes and penalties to impose. Those penalties could include <a href="https://digiday.com/marketing/whats-next-for-google-after-federal-judges-monopolization-ruling/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">restricting Google‚Äôs agreements</a> with Apple and other device or browser makers to allow other search engines to compete for those prime placements. Or Judge Mehta could decide to break Google up in some way, siloing pieces of the business into smaller entities.</p>
<p>Google has the opportunity to appeal the decision, which <a href="https://www.investopedia.com/google-says-it-will-appeal-antitrust-ruling-what-that-could-mean-for-big-tech-8690883" target="_blank" rel="noopener">it says</a> it plans to do. A potentially lengthy appeals process means it could be a while before we know the final outcome. ‚ÄúAt this time, the full impacts on search are unknown, and it could take a few years to fully see changes. But experts are predicting the ruling ‚Äòcould change how we use the internet and search for information,‚Äô‚Äù <a href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2024/08/05/google-loses-antitrust-case/74680072007/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">USA Today reported</a>.</p>
<div id="what-does-this-mean-for-small-businesses"></div>
<h2>What does this mean for small businesses?</h2>
<p>It could be years before we know the full impact of the ruling. But early reactions from industry experts suggest that it‚Äôs positive news for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/2025-marketing-planning">small businesses</a> and search engine users.</p>
<h3>Users and advertisers will have more search engine options</h3>
<p>One of the more likely outcomes is that smartphones and web browsers will need to <a href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2023/10/15/google-antitrust-trial-impact-search/71195279007/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">offer a range of search engines</a> to users‚Äîespecially when those systems are first initiated. That could lead to more overall investment in improving search and make way for new upstarts to join the search engine market.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Google-antitrust-ruling-choice-screen.webp" alt="Google antitrust ruling - Search engine choice screen as seen on European phones." width="292" height="552" class="aligncenter wp-image-85040 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Google-antitrust-ruling-choice-screen.webp 292w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Google-antitrust-ruling-choice-screen-159x300.webp 159w" sizes="(max-width: 292px) 100vw, 292px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>US Android users could see a search engine choice screen on device startup, similar to <a href="https://www.android.com/choicescreen/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the screen shown</a> to European Android users.</em></p>
<p>‚ÄúI do think it will open the door for more search platforms to have a fighting chance in more places, like on Apple devices, for example,‚Äù said Tony Testaverde, VP of Marketing Growth and Analytics at LocaliQ. ‚ÄúAnd it may open the door for more companies to invest in their own search engine.‚Äù Apple, for example, has toyed with the idea of building a search product to compete with Google, much the way it did with Apple Maps.</p>
<p>That last part is key since Judge Mehta specifically called out the reduced ‚Äúincentive to invest and innovate in search.‚Äù And while even <a href="https://www.theverge.com/24214574/google-antitrust-search-apple-microsoft-bing-ruling-breakdown" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Apple believes Google is the best search engine</a> currently, the carrot of greater access may prove to be the push Microsoft and others need to spend on innovation.</p>
<p>Brett McHale, a paid media marketing expert and the founder of Empiric Marketing, said the market is ready for more competitors and a more competitive search engine from Google. ‚ÄúMany people both within and outside of the industry have seen a deterioration in the quality of the search engine over the past few years,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúGoogle has rolled out so many SEO updates that it has become nearly impossible for smaller domains to rank effectively while simultaneously trying not to get penalized for once-accepted practices.‚Äù</p>
<p>The ruling cracked an opening in the search engine market, creating an opportunity for new players to compete against Google‚Äôs core product, said Katia Hausman, Vice President of Product Management at LocaliQ. ‚ÄúThe full impact of the court&#8217;s decision on the search industry remains to be seen. However, it&#8217;s likely to stimulate innovation beyond vertical search, where Google is already facing competition from Amazon and AI services. We could witness the emergence of new general search engines, leading to a more competitive market.‚Äù</p>
<p>McHale also believes that loosening the competitive constraints could help AI-powered search flourish. ‚ÄúCompanies like OpenAI and Meta have made great strides in that domain [AI-powered search] while Google has attempted to play catch-up with underwhelming results. We may see more competitors as a result, perhaps on the search engine side but I would anticipate more hybrid AI/search-related products to enter the space.‚Äù</p>
<h3>Lower advertising costs</h3>
<p>During testimony, a <a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/9/19/23880275/google-search-ads-competition-auction-prices-doj-trial-antitrust" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google ad executive admitted</a> that Google manipulated its ad auction process in a way that potentially increased prices by 5% for the typical advertiser and as much as 10% for some queries. While the search engine giant‚Äôs <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/2024-google-ads-benchmarks" target="_blank" rel="noopener">average cost per click has increased</a>, other advertising platforms like Facebook have seen <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/facebook-ads-benchmarks-2024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ad costs go down or stay flat</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Google-antitrust-ruling-ad-costs.webp" alt="Google antitrust ruling - screenshot of search ads costs from the WordStream Google ads benchmark report." width="855" height="508" class="aligncenter wp-image-85041 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Google-antitrust-ruling-ad-costs.webp 855w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Google-antitrust-ruling-ad-costs-480x285.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 855px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Google ads costs continue to increase, as noted in our 2024 <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/2024-google-ads-benchmarks">Google Ads Benchmarks Report</a>.</em></p>
<p>McHale said one of the best outcomes for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/small-business-saturday-marketing">small businesses</a> could be lower ad prices‚Äîor at least an end to the trend of ever-increasing costs.‚ÄúWe could see a drop in ad prices, or something similar to what happened to Google Shopping in 2017 in the EU‚Äîdue to a similar ruling‚Äîwhere third-party comparison shopping services were given a 20% discount on CPCs. In time, the landscape may improve considerably for small businesses with more opportunities and lower costs to advertise.‚Äù</p>
<p>Cliff Sizemore, a senior marketing manager at LocaliQ, agreed while noting that this is just one piece of a bigger picture. ‚ÄúI hope it will lower advertising costs and provide opportunities on different platforms, which would be a plus for small businesses,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúThere&#8217;s another trial on September 9 that covers Google&#8217;s ad tech, so we will be interested to see what comes of that.‚Äù</p>
<p>There could be increased pressure on each search engine to make its offering more attractive to advertisers. ‚ÄúEnd of the day, advertisers will always go back to where they are getting the highest ROI,‚Äù Testaverde said. ‚ÄúOpen ad cost competition will give more companies a chance to get their foot in the door. But the platforms and products need to prove profitable to businesses, or the dollars will eventually flow back to Google.‚Äù</p>
<h3>Diversifying ad spend becomes more important than ever</h3>
<p>With more search engine options for users comes more viable advertising platforms for small businesses. If more people use Google alternatives to find brands and products, small businesses will need to invest some of their marketing dollars in them to capture those leads.</p>
<p>‚ÄúDiversifying ad spend across multiple platforms is a wise strategy for small businesses, even without Google&#8217;s monopoly case,‚Äù Hausman said. ‚ÄúThis approach can yield better results by mitigating risks, lowering costs, and expanding reach. The potential changes in the search landscape due to the antitrust case make this strategy even more critical.‚Äù</p>
<p>Look for cross-platform advertising solutions and technology to become more important in the coming months and years as small businesses search for ways to maximize their returns from new advertising networks.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-antitrust-ruling">What the Google Antitrust Ruling Means for Advertisers &#038; Small Businesses</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Say Goodbye to a Cookieless Future: Google Reverses Decision</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-privacy-sandbox-update</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Susie Marino]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 24 Jul 2024 19:45:38 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Marketing News & Insights]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=84573</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Google says you can keep your cookies after all...here's what that means.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-privacy-sandbox-update">Say Goodbye to a Cookieless Future: Google Reverses Decision</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Google‚Äôs been yanking our chain about deprecating cookies for the last four years. They even started their phaseout in January of this year only to reverse their long-held stance and say JK‚Äîcookies aren‚Äôt going anywhere.</p>
<p>Google <a href="https://privacysandbox.com/intl/en_us/news/privacy-sandbox-update/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">recently announced</a> that it will be proposing an ‚Äúupdated approach‚Äù to the user experience on Google Chrome instead of deprecating third-party cookies. What exactly is changing and what does that all mean? Today, we‚Äôre covering just that!</p>
<h3><span>Contents</span></h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#what-is-happening">What‚Äôs happening?</a></li>
<li><a href="#why-was-google-phasing-out-cookies">Why was Google phasing out cookies?</a></li>
<li><a href="#what-is-google-doing-instead-of-phasing-out-cookies">What is Google doing instead of phasing out third-party cookies?</a></li>
<li><a href="#what-this-means">What does this mean for businesses?</a></li>
<li><a href="#ppc-community-sentiment">What the PPC community thinks about this change</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="what-is-happening"></div>
<h2>What‚Äôs happening?</h2>
<p>On July 22, Google <a href="https://privacysandbox.com/intl/en_us/news/privacy-sandbox-update/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">announced</a> a new path for its <a href="https://privacysandbox.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Privacy Sandbox</a> initiative on the web. This Privacy Sandbox project is the reason Google was originally going to phase out third-party cookies (in favor of first party data) in the second half of 2024.</p>
<p>Moving forward, however, <strong>Google will be keeping third-party cookies</strong>. Instead, the platform will offer ‚Äúopt in/opt out‚Äù options to Google Chrome users so they‚Äôre able to make choices and adjustments to their web browsing tracking preferences.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs the main statement from Google:</p>
<blockquote><p><em>&#8220;Instead of deprecating third-party cookies, we would introduce a new experience in Chrome that lets people make an informed choice that applies across their web browsing, and they‚Äôd be able to adjust that choice at any time. We&#8217;re discussing this new path with regulators and will engage with the industry as we roll this out.&#8221;</em></p></blockquote>
<p>Let‚Äôs break out some of the key terms from this announcement:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Third-party data: </strong>Aggregated customer information collected from third-party sources (cookies) across the web that your business can use but does not own.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/12/first-party-data" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>First-party data</strong></a><strong>: </strong>Internal information your business collects, owns, and holds.</li>
<li><strong>Privacy Sandbox: </strong>Google initiative that develops and releases privacy-focused APIs, advertiser and publisher tools, cookie updates, and more.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/types-of-customer-data.webp" alt="types of customer data" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-76534 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/types-of-customer-data.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/types-of-customer-data-480x308.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4a1.png" alt="üí°" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Whether you use first or third-party data for PPC, you can unlock opportunities to optimize your account with our free <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Ads Grader</a>.</p>
<div id="why-was-google-phasing-out-cookies"></div>
<h2>Why was Google phasing out cookies?</h2>
<p>Google was <a href="https://developers.google.com/privacy-sandbox/3pcd/prepare/prepare-for-phaseout" target="_blank" rel="noopener">phasing out third-party cookies</a> to move towards a more privacy-first web landscape that addressed concerns from users regarding how they‚Äôre being tracked online.</p>
<p>‚ÄúWe continue to invest in features that protect your data and provide more control over how it‚Äôs used. This includes taking steps to limit the ability to track your activity across different websites,‚Äù <a href="https://blog.google/products/chrome/privacy-sandbox-tracking-protection/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google said</a> regarding the initial decision to phase out third-party cookies.</p>
<p>The platform had planned to fully retire all third-party cookies by the end of this year, and this process had already started in January 2024‚Äîwhich, so far, only impacted about 1% of Chrome users.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/google-third-party-cookie-phase-out.webp" alt="google third-party cookie phase out timeline" width="936" height="381" class="aligncenter wp-image-81599 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/google-third-party-cookie-phase-out.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/google-third-party-cookie-phase-out-480x195.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="what-is-google-doing-instead-of-phasing-out-cookies"></div>
<h2>What is Google doing instead of phasing out third-party cookies?</h2>
<p>Google hasn‚Äôt yet released many details about the plan that will replace the third-party cookie phaseout. However, we do know that, <strong>while businesses still have the ability to track customer data via third-party cookies, Chrome users are going to have the option to ‚Äúopt out‚Äù of this tracking</strong>.</p>
<p>The Privacy Sandbox initiative will remain a priority for Google, and the plan is to continue to develop more privacy-first ways to accurately track and target audiences in Google Ads, GA4, and beyond.</p>
<p>‚ÄúAs this moves forward, it remains important for developers to have privacy-preserving alternatives. We&#8217;ll continue to make the Privacy Sandbox APIs available and invest in them to further improve privacy and utility. We also intend to offer additional privacy controls, so we plan to introduce <a href="https://developers.google.com/privacy-sandbox/protections/ip-protection" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IP Protection</a> into Chrome&#8217;s Incognito mode,‚Äù wrote Anthony Chavez, Vice President of Privacy Sandbox at Google, in the announcement article.</p>
<div id="what-this-means"></div>
<h2>What does this mean for your business</h2>
<p>If you‚Äôve shifted your strategy to primarily leverage first-party data, you‚Äôre still smart to do so. There are tons of effective, newer <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/preparing-for-ppc-success-in-cookieless-world" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PPC strategies that rely on first-party data</a>, like <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/04/17/how-to-set-up-google-ads-enhanced-conversions" target="_blank" rel="noopener">enhanced conversion bidding</a> or customer match audiences.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/how-enhanced-conversions-for-leads-work.webp" alt="how enhanced conversions for leads works in google ads" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-76940 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/how-enhanced-conversions-for-leads-work.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/how-enhanced-conversions-for-leads-work-480x308.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Plus, beyond Google, other platforms will also continue to push privacy-focused, first-party data driven strategies. For example, Facebook ads Advantage+ audiences can optimize your targeting based on the audience suggestions you provide.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/advantage-audience.webp" alt="facebook ads advantage+ audience screenshot" width="821" height="599" class="aligncenter wp-image-81604 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/advantage-audience.webp 821w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/advantage-audience-480x350.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 821px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f50d.png" alt="üîç" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Find¬†<a href="https://marketing.localiq.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsiteTargetAudience.html?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_TargetAudineceGuide_Download" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ways to find your target audience</a>, regardless of which type of data your business collects, in this free guide!</p>
<div id="ppc-community-sentiment"></div>
<h2>What industry experts are saying about this change</h2>
<p>For the most part, this change is welcome, as Google even called out in its original announcement article that the deprecation of third-party cookies was putting stress on many advertisers.</p>
<p>‚ÄúWe expect that overall performance using Privacy Sandbox APIs will <a href="https://privacysandbox.com/news/learnings-from-privacy-sandbox-testing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">improve</a> over time as industry adoption increases. At the same time, we recognize this transition requires significant work by many participants and will have an impact on publishers, advertisers, and everyone involved in online advertising,‚Äù said Anthony.</p>
<p>And some advertisers agree‚Äîanything could be better than the sunset of third-party cookies. For example, <a href="https://x.com/SeoTudent/status/1815492760956493918" target="_blank" rel="noopener">this X post</a> below acknowledges that third-party cookie deprecation would have put a ton of businesses out of business.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-ads-no-longer-deprecating-third-party-cookies-x.webp" alt="google ads privacy sandbox update - third-party cookie deprecation reaction" width="597" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84580 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-ads-no-longer-deprecating-third-party-cookies-x.webp 597w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-ads-no-longer-deprecating-third-party-cookies-x-480x482.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 597px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>But if you feel like you‚Äôve dedicated a lot of work to prepare for a cookie-less future, you‚Äôre not alone. Other advertisers, as shown in <a href="https://x.com/robinberjon/status/1815473283271205203" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the following X post</a>, aren‚Äôt happy that the time spent preparing (and worrying) about the demise of third-party cookies is now, in some ways, wasted.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-third-party-cookie-plan-x-post.webp" alt="google privacy sandbox change - x post screenshot" width="409" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84576 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-third-party-cookie-plan-x-post.webp 409w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-third-party-cookie-plan-x-post-205x300.webp 205w" sizes="(max-width: 409px) 100vw, 409px" /></p>
<p>Plus, the lack of clarity around the new path for Google Chrome isn‚Äôt giving advertisers much faith, either.</p>
<p>&#8220;That, based on historical evidence, could end up being a big win for advertisers, as most users simply won‚Äôt make any changes to their settings. But then again, if Google starts prompting users with pop-ups, like Apple does with ATT, that could also end up being significantly worse too, and see much less user data flowing through,‚Äù writes Andrew Hutchinson, Content and Social Media Manager at Social Media Today, in <a href="https://www.socialmediatoday.com/news/google-abandons-plan-phase-tracking-cookies/722069/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">this article</a>.</p>
<p>Ari Paparo, CEO at Marketecture, added his guess on what the Chrome update will look like in the following <a href="https://x.com/aripap/status/1815462762191196614" target="_blank" rel="noopener">X post</a>, where he says:</p>
<p>‚ÄúMy guess is they‚Äôre going to slowly move from opt out of third-party cookies, to recommending blocking to users, then eventually to opt in only.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-change-x-post.webp" alt="google privacy sandbox change - chrome update prediction" width="629" height="256" class="aligncenter wp-image-84577 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-change-x-post.webp 629w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-change-x-post-480x195.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 629px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>These sentiments reiterate the fact that your first-party data will continue to be important as less potential customers may opt into third-party tracking in the future.</p>
<p>The update also raises questions around <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/23/google-analytics-4-vs-universal-analytics">Google Analytics 4</a> (GA4), since it was known that one of the main reasons GA4 replaced Universal Analytics was to allow for more first-party tracking capabilities.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-update-ga4.webp" alt="google privacy sandbox update - ga4 mention" width="587" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84579 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-update-ga4.webp 587w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-update-ga4-480x491.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 587px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://x.com/tmcvin/status/1815745640393036122" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-ua.webp" alt="google privacy sandbox update - google universal analytics mention" width="514" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84578 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-ua.webp 514w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-ua-480x560.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 514px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://x.com/mik_126/status/1815501964102586515" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></em></p>
<p>The bottom line? <strong>Advertisers are feeling like this is yet another curveball from Google, and the platform will have to step up its Privacy Sandbox game</strong> to make more first-party data PPC strategies truly worthwhile.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-update-bottom-line.webp" alt="google privacy sandbox announcement - bottom line post screenshot" width="538" height="565" class="aligncenter wp-image-84581 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-update-bottom-line.webp 538w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/google-privacy-sandbox-update-bottom-line-480x504.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 538px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://x.com/LexGabrees/status/1815750055493562531" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></em></p>
<h2>The Google Privacy Sandbox plot thickens</h2>
<p>Advertisers will have to wait for more information from Google as it begins to roll out Chrome tracking controls to users.</p>
<p>Cookie-less or not, all forms of data can be valuable to your business, so it&#8217;s best to continue your mix of first-party and third-party strategies. Staying informed as Google releases more updates is your best bet right now!</p>
